---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Figure from "../components/Figure.astro";
import Reframe from "../components/diagrams/Reframe.astro";
import TheDoor from "../components/diagrams/TheDoor.astro";
---

<Base>
  <!-- ======================= HERO ======================= -->
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="container hero-inner">
      <p class="tagline">Life evolves and so can we</p>
      <h1>Most people try to change their lives. I help them understand why their lives make sense.</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Whether the thing you want to change is your own life or how your company works, it usually comes down to
        the same surprise: people make a lot more sense than they seem to, once you can see what's really going on.
      </p>
      <div class="btn-row">
        <a href="/personal-work" class="btn btn-primary">Start Personal Work</a>
        <a href="/professional-work" class="btn btn-outline">Bring This to Your Team</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======================= RECOGNITION INTRO ======================= -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <p>You already know how this goes. The promise to speak up next time. The apology you didn't owe. The meeting that ended in agreement and fell apart in the parking lot.</p>
      <p>You've read the books and tried the strategies. You can describe the problem in detail, which is somehow the most frustrating part, because understanding it from the outside hasn't changed it.</p>
      <p>Here's why. The pattern you can't seem to break is doing a job. It makes sense to a part of you, even when it doesn't make sense on the surface. That's why trying harder never quite works: you can't out-muscle something you haven't found.</p>
      <p class="lead" style="margin-top:1.5rem;">But you can change it once you find it. The moment you understand why it keeps happening, you finally get to do something else.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======================= THE TURN ======================= -->
  <section class="section-tight bg-cream2 turn">
    <div class="container narrow center">
      <p class="eyebrow">The turn</p>
      <p class="lead turn-line">
        Here's the good news. You make sense, too. Even the things you wish you'd stop doing have a logic underneath
        them. Once you can see that logic, change stops feeling like a fight with yourself and starts feeling like a decision.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======================= WHERE THIS SHOWS UP ======================= -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="center" style="margin-bottom:3rem;">
        <p class="eyebrow">Where this shows up</p>
        <h2>Different rooms. Same thing underneath.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="two-col">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>In your life</h3>
          <ul class="ticklist">
            <li>You replay conversations at night, rewriting what you said.</li>
            <li>You agreed to something yesterday that you resented by this morning.</li>
            <li>You can feel yourself disappearing into a relationship, and you keep choosing it anyway.</li>
            <li>You achieved the things. You're still waiting for the feeling that was supposed to come with them.</li>
            <li>You know exactly what you'd tell a friend in your situation. You just can't take the advice.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>At work</h3>
          <ul class="ticklist">
            <li>The meeting ends, and the real meeting starts in the parking lot.</li>
            <li>You said it clearly. They heard something else. Now there are two stories.</li>
            <li>Everyone agrees on the goal and keeps colliding on the way there.</li>
            <li>There's a person everyone has quietly learned to work around, and it's costing more than anyone says out loud.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="narrow" style="margin-top:2.5rem; text-align:center;">
        The behavior is real. It just isn't the whole story. Once you understand what someone is actually protecting,
        yourself included, confusion starts turning into clarity. And when something finally makes sense, you know what
        to do with it.
      </p>
      <Figure max={640} caption="One behavior, one fast conclusion, and the questions that crack it back open.">
        <Reframe />
      </Figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======================= TWO DOORS ======================= -->
  <section class="section bg-cream2">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="center" style="margin-bottom:2.75rem;">
        <h2>Two doors</h2>
      </div>
      <Figure max={560} plain caption="Every pattern is a door. On the other side is the story it was built to protect.">
        <TheDoor />
      </Figure>
      <div class="two-col doors-2">
        <div class="doorway">
          <span class="door-extras" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <h3>Personal Work</h3>
          <p>Maybe you've been working on this for years. Maybe you just woke up one day and realized something isn't right. Either way, the problem probably isn't what you think it is. And it probably isn't you.</p>
          <p>The parts of your life that feel most frustrating usually aren't random. They were solutions to something. Once you understand what they were solving, change stops feeling like such a struggle.</p>
          <a href="/personal-work" class="arrow-link">Explore Personal Work <span class="arrow">→</span></a>
        </div>
        <div class="doorway">
          <span class="door-extras" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <h3>Professional Work</h3>
          <p>There's no such thing as just business. Every project, every deadline, every difficult conversation runs through a person.</p>
          <p>You've built the operating systems: the processes, the tools, the way the work flows. Every one of them runs on people, on what they assume, what they trust, what they say or don't say to each other. That's the human system underneath the work, and it's the one most companies never actually build. When people feel understood, they stop protecting and start participating, and the work gets easier everywhere at once.</p>
          <a href="/professional-work" class="arrow-link">Bring This to Your Team <span class="arrow">→</span></a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======================= WHAT MAKES THIS DIFFERENT ======================= -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow center">What makes this different</p>
      <p>You've already tried. The honest conversations. The boundaries that didn't stick. The system that lasted a month. It worked for a little while, and then you ended up back where you started, carrying the extra weight of having failed at the fixing too.</p>
      <p>Effort was never the problem. A pattern you don't understand will quietly outlast every strategy you throw at it.</p>
      <p>So we don't start with strategies. We start underneath, with the why behind this particular thing that keeps happening. Sometimes that's the whole turn: you see that the reason no longer holds, and it quietly loses its grip. Sometimes seeing it isn't enough on its own, and we keep going, updating old emotional learning that's been running on outdated information, or letting yourself feel the thing you've spent years avoiding and discovering you survive it.</p>
      <p class="lead">The difference is that now nothing inside you is fighting it. The change holds because it isn't being forced.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======================= MEET CANDACE ======================= -->
  <section class="section bg-cream2">
    <div class="container meet-grid">
      <div class="meet-photo">
        <div class="photo-frame">
          <span class="photo-note">Photo: Candace, in real light</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="meet-copy">
        <p class="eyebrow">Meet Candace</p>
        <p class="lead">I help people understand the why underneath what they do, the part that usually stays out of view.</p>
        <p>Individuals who keep running into the same wall and can't see why. Leaders who are brilliant with strategy and baffled by their own team. People who built everything they wanted and woke up feeling flat.</p>
        <p>Part of my week is spent helping individuals make sense of themselves, the other part helping teams make sense of each other. What I've found, every single time, is that people make sense. Not eventually, not once they've changed, but right now, exactly as they are, for reasons that can be found.</p>
        <p>Finding those reasons is the work, and it's the work I'm best at.</p>
        <a href="/about" class="arrow-link">More about me <span class="arrow">→</span></a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======================= UNDERSTANDING → CLARITY → CAPABILITY ======================= -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow center">
      <h2>Understanding. Then clarity. Then capability.</h2>
      <p>That's the whole job, in that order, because it doesn't work in any other.</p>
      <blockquote class="quote">
        Everything makes sense now. I know what to do. And I feel capable of doing it.
        <cite>a client, after our work together</cite>
      </blockquote>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ======================= START HERE ======================= -->
  <section class="section bg-teal start">
    <div class="container narrow center">
      <p class="eyebrow">Start here</p>
      <h2>You don't need to arrive with it figured out.</h2>
      <p style="color:#cfe0e2; max-width:60ch; margin-inline:auto;">
        You only need to arrive curious about why your life works the way it does. Bring the thing that keeps happening:
        the relationship that hurts, the team that's stuck, the decision you've been circling for a year. We'll find what
        it's protecting, and then we'll decide together what to do about it.
      </p>
      <div class="btn-row" style="justify-content:center; margin-top:1.75rem;">
        <a href="/personal-work" class="btn btn-primary">Start Personal Work</a>
        <a href="/professional-work" class="btn btn-outline">Bring This to Your Team</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  /* hero */
  .hero {
    background:
      radial-gradient(120% 80% at 85% 0%, #fdf4e2 0%, rgba(253,244,226,0) 55%),
      linear-gradient(180deg, #fdfaf3 0%, var(--cream) 100%);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line);
  }
  .hero-inner {
    padding-block: clamp(4rem, 11vw, 8.5rem) clamp(3.5rem, 9vw, 7rem);
    max-width: 940px;
  }
  .hero-inner .tagline { margin-bottom: 1.25rem; }
  .hero-inner h1 { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; max-width: 18ch; }
  .hero-inner .lead { margin-bottom: 2.25rem; max-width: 56ch; color: var(--body); }

  /* the turn */
  .turn-line { color: var(--ink); }

  /* two-column blocks */
  .two-col { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: clamp(1.25rem, 3vw, 2rem); }
  .two-col h3 { color: var(--teal-900); }

  /* two-doors row: a touch more breathing room between the two doorways */
  .doors-2 { gap: clamp(1.5rem, 4vw, 3rem); max-width: 860px; margin-inline: auto; }
  .doorway h3 { color: var(--teal-900); text-align: center; }

  /* meet candace */
  .meet-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 0.85fr 1.15fr;
    gap: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 4rem);
    align-items: center;
  }
  .photo-frame {
    aspect-ratio: 4 / 5;
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    background: linear-gradient(160deg, var(--teal-tint), var(--cream-3));
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    display: grid;
    place-items: center;
    box-shadow: var(--shadow-sm);
  }
  .photo-note { font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--muted); font-style: italic; }

  /* quote */
  .quote {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 2.6vw, 1.9rem);
    line-height: 1.35;
    color: var(--teal-900);
    font-style: italic;
    max-width: 24ch;
    margin: 2.25rem auto 0;
    position: relative;
  }
  .quote cite { display: block; font-family: var(--font-sans); font-size: 0.92rem; font-style: normal; color: var(--muted); margin-top: 1rem; letter-spacing: 0.02em; }

  /* start band */
  .start h2 { max-width: 22ch; margin-inline: auto; }

  @media (max-width: 860px) {
    .two-col { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .meet-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .meet-photo { max-width: 420px; }
  }
</style>
